        ...to hedge against the terror of having a terrible memory. Though still
        young enough to expect no sympathy, I constantly feel the burden of this
        handicap. Confirmation of it, and that writing is its cure, I discover
        every time I pick up something I wrote years, or even months ago.
        Reading those things puts me in an uncanny state, like a past-life
        regression. Meanwhile, unrecorded impressions, sayings, old friends, and
        good books vanish without warning or trace. Some read and write to win
        eternal life; I would be happy enough just to keep a hold of this one.
      </span><br />
      <span class="not-italic">– Nathan Schneider</span>
    </blockquote>
  </section>

